snippet.textDisplay: Cleetus, I'm sure you are tired of hearing from me, but here goes again- free advice, worth exactly what you paid for it; when you go looking for that "bucket truck", include in your search a "telephone pole setting truck"- they have a hydraulic, folding arm  and sufficient power and versatility to drill the 12" hole, lift the telephone pole (#2500-#3400), stick it in the hole and hold it level and then has a bucket the linemen can work from to set the trees and hardware for service as a carrier. They also generally have large capacity tool boxes as part of the bed, and quite often are cabbed with 4 door cabs. Love the core sample idea- not only will it tell the history of the tracks construction, it may tell you a great deal regarding future maintenance needs. I hope you got the builder's comment about the portability of the far side bleachers- that means you could move them to a better vantage, only needing to install proper support pads for the structure.
snippet.textOriginal: Cleetus, I'm sure you are tired of hearing from me, but here goes again- free advice, worth exactly what you paid for it; when you go looking for that "bucket truck", include in your search a "telephone pole setting truck"- they have a hydraulic, folding arm  and sufficient power and versatility to drill the 12" hole, lift the telephone pole (#2500-#3400), stick it in the hole and hold it level and then has a bucket the linemen can work from to set the trees and hardware for service as a carrier. snippet.textDisplay: It's nice that Mr. Tharpe saved those original drawings for the facility.  It will save a lot of time and expense when renovating. Those pole mounted fuse boxes were perhaps a good way to save money 40 years ago when operating on a shoestring budget.  But I'd see about relocating them on the ground level and upgrading the fuses to circuit breakers.  Way easier to maintain and not that much to install especially if rewiring for LED's anyway.
snippet.textOriginal: It's nice that Mr. Tharpe saved those original drawings for the facility.  It will save a lot of time and expense when renovating. Those pole mounted fuse boxes were perhaps a good way to save money 40 years ago when operating on a shoestring budget. snippet.textDisplay: This is awesome! Imagine your dream, something you made, people lose interest in it, or someone buys it and let's it degrade and you can't do anything about it. Years later, a few generations later, some younger kids with similar ideology see a diamond in the ruff and buy it. The faith restored in that old man, seeing people a few generations younger, taking his original dream and bringing it back to life, will probably make him happy come the day he passes knowing he left a legacy that another generation is picking up on and will keep alive for years to come!
